{"focus":{"id":"60415f42-a535-5264-8784-75d2430d80b6","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba13b7c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.NS.A.2.a","description":"Understand that multiplication is extended from fractions to rational numbers by requiring that operations continue to satisfy the properties of operations, particularly the distributive property, leading to products such as (-1)(-1) = 1 and the rules for multiplying signed numbers. Interpret products of rational numbers by describing real-world contexts.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"NS","cluster":"7.NS.A","level":"substandard"},"ancestors":[{"id":"0eb3e5dd-ea32-5ff9-9b5c-9806c54bbbdc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dd100-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.2","description":"Solve addition and subtraction word problems, and add and subtract within 10, e.g., by using objects or drawings to represent the problem.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"b978b10f-234d-5964-89ed-c132adc07a1f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ca104-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.1","description":"Represent addition and subtraction with objects, fingers, mental images, drawings, sounds (e.g., claps), acting out situations, verbal explanations, expressions, or equations.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"b2e2c061-29b5-5946-be19-19e1a5e8e148","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e93c4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.3","description":"Decompose numbers less than or equal to 10 into pairs in more than one way, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record each decomposition by a drawing or equation (e.g., 5 = 2 + 3 and 5 = 4 + 1).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"9dfd6529-b354-556c-9f2a-3d278234cae4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f318e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.4","description":"For any number from 1 to 9, find the number that makes 10 when added to the given number, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record the answer with a drawing or equation.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ec423f7c-3e67-5b0c-9f72-c5fd236b2b61","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fc478-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.5","description":"Fluently add and subtract within 5.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"f2f75947-1ec6-5a93-b1a4-4931db79b461","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9da7-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.NBT.A.1","description":"Compose and decompose numbers from 11 to 19 into ten ones and some further ones, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record each composition or decomposition by a drawing or equation (e.g., 18 = 10 + 8); understand that these numbers are composed of ten ones and one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, or nine ones.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"NBT","cluster":"K.NBT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"6e056208-42cb-524f-bfcf-793bffdaf9a0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba250cd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.CC.B.4.c","description":"Understand that each successive number name refers to a quantity that is one larger.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"CC","cluster":"K.CC.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"0465e0ad-eaf2-5d3e-999f-fe665744aaf1","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9637-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.CC.A.1","description":"Count to 100 by ones and by tens.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"CC","cluster":"K.CC.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"2736f26a-1e5c-5b90-be28-5f4c801bfd82","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba030d6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.B.6","description":"Compose simple shapes to form larger shapes. *For example, \"Can you join these two triangles with full sides touching to make a rectangle?\"*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"96c55133-2681-59f9-93af-d27881cbf101","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dce41-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.MD.A.2","description":"Directly compare two objects with a measurable attribute in common, to see which object has \"more of\"/\"less of\" the attribute, and describe the difference. *For example, directly compare the heights of two children and describe one child as taller/shorter.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"MD","cluster":"K.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"472fb1eb-7c0d-5904-b9a3-e5a6d94b4ab3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9896-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.1","description":"Describe objects in the environment using names of shapes, and describe the relative positions of these objects using terms such as above, below, beside, in front of, behind, and next to.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"308440b4-e522-5061-85a6-4a5a0a3dce51","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dcb8a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.2","description":"Correctly name shapes regardless of their orientations or overall size.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d4594d7e-edbd-5c0b-a233-35cccdbbcecf","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e8f43-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.3","description":"Identify shapes as two-dimensional (lying in a plane, \"flat\") or three-dimensional (\"solid\").","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"fb8a2e0d-695f-556f-be81-53427c5011dc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9af3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.MD.A.1","description":"Describe measurable attributes of objects, such as length or weight. Describe several measurable attributes of a single object.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"MD","cluster":"K.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"6f455e8e-dcc3-5836-8926-5a726e009306","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e0fbe-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.B.3","description":"Apply properties of operations as strategies to add and subtract.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"3aa19a18-9443-5552-899b-063648313211","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ebb03-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.B.4","description":"Understand subtraction as an unknown-addend problem. *For example, subtract 10 - 8 by finding the number that makes 10 when added to 8.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"bbc995ce-7cd3-59c6-896d-64a23b2ee989","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba09818-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.D.8","description":"Determine the unknown whole number in an addition or subtraction equation relating three whole numbers. *For example, determine the unknown number that makes the equation true in each of the equations $8 + ? = 11, 5 = \\Box  - 3, 6 + 6 = \\Box$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"e2ac303d-3864-56f1-b848-aa5bdcc8d14b","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bdee1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.A.1","description":"Use addition and subtraction within 20 to solve word problems involving situations of adding to, taking from, putting together, taking apart, and comparing, with unknowns in all positions, e.g., by using objects, drawings, and equations with a symbol for the unknown number to represent the problem.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"329754ec-5f10-5e72-b72c-f10e015e88a8","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9eb89a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.NBT.C.4","description":"Add within 100, including adding a two-digit number and a one-digit number, and adding a two-digit number and a multiple of 10, using concrete models or drawings and strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction; relate the strategy to a written method and explain the reasoning used. Understand that in adding two-digit numbers, one adds tens and tens, ones and ones; and sometimes it is necessary to compose a ten.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"NBT","cluster":"1.NBT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"4dab7809-d18a-591f-862d-86e8d5785a03","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f4fd0-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.NBT.C.5","description":"Given a two-digit number, mentally find 10 more or 10 less than the number, without having to count; explain the reasoning used.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"NBT","cluster":"1.NBT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"e698ee8c-edbe-5fac-87ae-cf9c8ef770c7","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fd080-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.NBT.C.6","description":"Subtract multiples of 10 in the range 10-90 from multiples of 10 in the range 10-90 (positive or zero differences), using concrete models or drawings and strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction; relate the strategy to a written method and explain the reasoning used.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"NBT","cluster":"1.NBT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"1208a51d-bbaa-5d92-8192-758a71391c59","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba03a8f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.D.7","description":"Understand the meaning of the equal sign, and determine if equations involving addition and subtraction are true or false. *For example, which of the following equations are true and which are false? 6 = 6, 7 = 8 - 1, 5 + 2 = 2 + 5, 4 + 1 = 5 + 2.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"aa0c5592-b771-525d-a9a4-e7579b266e1f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fd4e5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.C.6","description":"Add and subtract within 20, demonstrating fluency for addition and subtraction within 10. Use strategies such as counting on; making ten (e.g., 8 + 6 = 8 + 2 + 4 = 10 + 4 = 14); decomposing a number leading to a ten (e.g., 13 - 4 = 13 - 3 - 1 = 10 - 1 = 9); using the relationship between addition and subtraction (e.g., knowing that 8 + 4 = 12, one knows 12 - 8 = 4); and creating equivalent but easier or known sums (e.g., adding 6 + 7 by creating the known equivalent 6 + 6 + 1 = 12 + 1 = 13).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"827a633a-b88a-5ce9-8a7a-18369c547363","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d22e5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.NBT.B.2","description":"Understand that the two digits of a two-digit number represent amounts of tens and ones. Understand the following as special cases:","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"NBT","cluster":"1.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"39db4dc2-ac27-54cd-b78a-b65d512eb8a6","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e0945-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.G.A.3","description":"Partition circles and rectangles into two and four equal shares, describe the shares using the words halves, fourths, and quarters, and use the phrases half of, fourth of, and quarter of. Describe the whole as two of, or four of the shares. Understand for these examples that decomposing into more equal shares creates smaller shares.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"G","cluster":"1.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"78ed3ab1-18c4-59c1-9aee-da9d8800d08c","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f527f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.C.5","description":"Relate counting to addition and subtraction (e.g., by counting on 2 to add 2).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"db51575f-e92e-5a08-904b-66b7b1a5a656","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bdbaf-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.NBT.A.1","description":"Count to 120, starting at any number less than 120. In this range, read and write numerals and represent a number of objects with a written numeral.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"NBT","cluster":"1.NBT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"5202eb12-da14-59b3-aaca-d84bfb21b73d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d205c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.MD.A.2","description":"Express the length of an object as a whole number of length units, by laying multiple copies of a shorter object (the length unit) end to end; understand that the length measurement of an object is the number of same-size length units that span it with no gaps or overlaps.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"MD","cluster":"1.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"226b21e4-6dd2-53ce-bd17-68b5c61d3093","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d1dd5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.G.A.2","description":"Compose two-dimensional shapes (rectangles, squares, trapezoids, triangles, half-circles, and quarter-circles) or three-dimensional shapes (cubes, right rectangular prisms, right circular cones, and right circular cylinders) to create a composite shape, and compose new shapes from the composite shape.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"G","cluster":"1.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"a5c72e23-4039-51b9-8ab3-86f4708d7381","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bd85b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.MD.A.1","description":"Order three objects by length; compare the lengths of two objects indirectly by using a third object.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"MD","cluster":"1.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"3460571a-4af1-5be2-8300-f1b3d5dec056","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9beba4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.OA.A.1","description":"Use addition and subtraction within 100 to solve one- and two-step word problems involving situations of adding to, taking from, putting together, taking apart, and comparing, with unknowns in all positions, e.g., by using drawings and equations with a symbol for the unknown number to represent the problem.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"OA","cluster":"2.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"a1310b6d-2e79-5226-9bf9-03c16ac02af5","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d2bdf-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.MD.A.2","description":"Measure the length of an object twice, using length units of different lengths for the two measurements; describe how the two measurements relate to the size of the unit chosen.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"MD","cluster":"2.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"50aa6eb6-7f6b-5286-80d9-67e719722c54","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e11e8-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.G.A.3","description":"Partition circles and rectangles into two, three, or four equal shares, describe the shares using the words halves, thirds, half of, a third of, etc., and describe the whole as two halves, three thirds, four fourths. Recognize that equal shares of identical wholes need not have the same shape.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"G","cluster":"2.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d865f537-3bc8-5143-81b9-3ade20de09d2","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fd7e9-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.MD.B.6","description":"Represent whole numbers as lengths from 0 on a number line diagram with equally spaced points corresponding to the numbers 0, 1, 2, …, and represent whole-number sums and differences within 100 on a number line diagram.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"MD","cluster":"2.MD.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"1e7b8f46-92a9-5817-ba90-cf67a66bc81a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9be543-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.MD.A.1","description":"Measure the length of an object by selecting and using appropriate tools such as rulers, yardsticks, meter sticks, and measuring tapes.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"MD","cluster":"2.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"34042f6f-b54d-5958-8fd1-2b6a24836e62","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e1402-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.MD.A.3","description":"Estimate lengths using units of inches, feet, centimeters, and meters.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"MD","cluster":"2.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"73138360-d2c3-53b0-aa36-91b9ea38f0f8","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d290b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.G.A.2","description":"Partition a rectangle into rows and columns of same-size squares and count to find the total number of them.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"G","cluster":"2.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"75f88ede-4b74-51ba-b1e5-2e2d8bd759a6","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e188a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.OA.C.3","description":"Determine whether a group of objects (up to 20) has an odd or even number of members, e.g., by pairing objects or counting them by 2s; write an equation to express an even number as a sum of two equal addends.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"OA","cluster":"2.OA.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"5364ad93-e6c0-51b2-8e09-9466691c324a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ec21d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.OA.C.4","description":"Use addition to find the total number of objects arranged in rectangular arrays with up to 5 rows and up to 5 columns; write an equation to express the total as a sum of equal addends.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"OA","cluster":"2.OA.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"53dd1dc9-19ab-582c-8014-de8981768e5d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e210d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.NF.A.3","description":"Explain equivalence of fractions in special cases, and compare fractions by reasoning about their size.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"NF","cluster":"3.NF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"e1755456-c533-5a84-891e-59725c0479e0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bf846-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.NF.A.1","description":"Understand a fraction $\\frac{1}{b}$ as the quantity formed by 1 part when a whole is partitioned into b equal parts; understand a fraction $\\frac{a}{b}$ as the quantity formed by a parts of size $\\frac{1}{b}$.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"NF","cluster":"3.NF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"40edda9b-7aed-5802-8bff-d566f71df50d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d400d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.NF.A.2","description":"Understand a fraction as a number on the number line; represent fractions on a number line diagram.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"NF","cluster":"3.NF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"7fb27036-f1e3-5214-b65d-2333e20186be","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e233f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.A.3","description":"Use multiplication and division within 100 to solve word problems in situations involving equal groups, arrays, and measurement quantities, e.g., by using drawings and equations with a symbol for the unknown number to represent the problem.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"affc10f3-aae4-58ea-bc33-ed9fae9be609","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bfb73-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.A.1","description":"Interpret products of whole numbers, e.g., interpret $5 \\times 7$ as the total number of objects in 5 groups of 7 objects each. *For example, describe a context in which a total number of objects can be expressed as $5 \\div 7$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"64cb2ac3-6f8d-55f5-bbae-6e4de98768e3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d430d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.A.2","description":"Interpret whole-number quotients of whole numbers, e.g., interpret $56 \\div 8$ as the number of objects in each share when 56 objects are partitioned equally into 8 shares, or as a number of shares when 56 objects are partitioned into equal shares of 8 objects each. *For example, describe a context in which a number of shares or a number of groups can be expressed as $56 \\div 8$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"6189b37a-9eff-5aed-bad5-9e59619fd396","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c09e2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NF.A.1","description":"Explain why a fraction $\\frac{a}{b}$ is equivalent to a fraction $\\frac{(n \\times a)}{(n \\times b)}$ by using visual fraction models, with attention to how the number and size of the parts differ even though the two fractions themselves are the same size. Use this principle to recognize and generate equivalent fractions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NF","cluster":"4.NF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"eb63f464-897f-53b3-8ea5-bd965e4a7da6","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1136b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NF.B.3.a","description":"Understand addition and subtraction of fractions as joining and separating parts referring to the same whole.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NF","cluster":"4.NF.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"9ea3d69d-56ed-5685-a4d0-e93262f46423","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba18d83-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NF.B.3.b","description":"Decompose a fraction into a sum of fractions with the same denominator in more than one way, recording each decomposition by an equation. Justify decompositions, e.g., by using a visual fraction model.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NF","cluster":"4.NF.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"a65d0bd0-f7c2-52da-b2db-3a29816bd244","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba208b6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NF.B.3.c","description":"Add and subtract mixed numbers with like denominators, e.g., by replacing each mixed number with an equivalent fraction, and/or by using properties of operations and the relationship between addition and subtraction.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NF","cluster":"4.NF.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"e89d12eb-613d-5825-ac2d-c435cc3b1564","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba25f3e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NF.B.3.d","description":"Solve word problems involving addition and subtraction of fractions referring to the same whole and having like denominators, e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NF","cluster":"4.NF.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"743db505-fe65-55ff-bac5-574e41555291","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d51bd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.OA.A.2","description":"Multiply or divide to solve word problems involving multiplicative comparison, e.g., by using drawings and equations with a symbol for the unknown number to represent the problem, distinguishing multiplicative comparison from additive comparison.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"OA","cluster":"4.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d968d12f-9a8c-5cd8-aee3-f87f496b49cd","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c1a30-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.NF.A.1","description":"Add and subtract fractions with unlike denominators (including mixed numbers) by replacing given fractions with equivalent fractions in such a way as to produce an equivalent sum or difference of fractions with like denominators. *For example, $\\frac{2}{3} + \\frac{5}{4} = \\frac{8}{12} + \\frac{15}{12} = \\frac{23}{12}$. (In general, $\\frac{a}{b} + \\frac{c}{d} = \\frac{(ad + bc)}{bd}$.)*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"NF","cluster":"5.NF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"16d9b4d6-86de-58c8-ad92-8c44938cc71a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba12b02-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.NS.C.6.a","description":"Recognize opposite signs of numbers as indicating locations on opposite sides of 0 on the number line; recognize that the opposite of the opposite of a number is the number itself, e.g., -(-3) = 3, and that 0 is its own opposite.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"NS","cluster":"6.NS.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"9da513f5-6ac1-5768-a441-6c24aad943ea","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba21b2c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.NS.C.7.c","description":"Understand the absolute value of a rational number as its distance from 0 on the number line; interpret absolute value as magnitude for a positive or negative quantity in a real-world situation. *For example, for an account balance of -30 dollars, write |-30| = 30 to describe the size of the debt in dollars.*","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"NS","cluster":"6.NS.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"164ff7f2-0152-551a-969f-437aed471786","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f77af-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.NS.C.5","description":"Understand that positive and negative numbers are used together to describe quantities having opposite directions or values (e.g., temperature above/below zero, elevation above/below sea level, credits/debits, positive/negative electric charge); use positive and negative numbers to represent quantities in real-world contexts, explaining the meaning of 0 in each situation.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"NS","cluster":"6.NS.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"cf5df918-2d02-5743-9c38-1476d52f11f6","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba26d02-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.NS.A.1.d","description":"Apply properties of operations as strategies to add and subtract rational numbers.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"NS","cluster":"7.NS.A","level":"substandard"},{"id":"a1d441d7-d499-5654-a7bd-8ef360893cde","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1b8b8-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.NS.A.1.b","description":"Understand p + q as the number located a distance |q| from p, in the positive or negative direction depending on whether q is positive or negative. Show that a number and its opposite have a sum of 0 (are additive inverses). Interpret sums of rational numbers by describing real-world contexts.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"NS","cluster":"7.NS.A","level":"substandard"},{"id":"ba4cefdb-67e9-536a-8187-e9022ea9b28e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba224e2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.NS.A.1.c","description":"Understand subtraction of rational numbers as adding the additive inverse, p - q = p + (-q). Show that the distance between two rational numbers on the number line is the absolute value of their difference, and apply this principle in real-world contexts.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"NS","cluster":"7.NS.A","level":"substandard"}],"descendants":[],"edges":[{"id":"23a99f08-73b9-5e2c-a4f6-ac3c0fcad1f8","label":"buildsTowards","source":"0465e0ad-eaf2-5d3e-999f-fe665744aaf1","target":"db51575f-e92e-5a08-904b-66b7b1a5a656"},{"id":"11ba9df0-bde6-5d07-af54-3b704cb0f906","label":"buildsTowards","source":"6e056208-42cb-524f-bfcf-793bffdaf9a0","target":"78ed3ab1-18c4-59c1-9aee-da9d8800d08c"},{"id":"ebaaf738-0897-5a48-bb0a-badcb6b4d512","label":"buildsTowards","source":"b978b10f-234d-5964-89ed-c132adc07a1f","target":"0eb3e5dd-ea32-5ff9-9b5c-9806c54bbbdc"},{"id":"ffd9d939-2694-5796-b4fc-b2427a3235cb","label":"buildsTowards","source":"0eb3e5dd-ea3